          "body": "The theological distance between chapter 18 and chapter 19 is the distance between wet clay and fired ceramic. In chapter 18, the pot on the wheel was marred, and the potter reshaped it — still plastic, still workable, still responsive to the craftsman's hand. The LORD used that image to say: 'If that nation against which I have spoken turns from its evil, I will relent' (18:8). Chapter 19 opens not with a potter at his wheel but with a command to purchase a *baqbuq* — a finished, narrow-necked, fired vessel. When it shatters at verse 10, the LORD says it 'cannot again be repaired.' The Hebrew is *lo' yukhal lehiraphe'* — literally 'it is not able to be healed.' This is the same root (*rapha*) used for divine healing elsewhere in Jeremiah (3:22; 17:14; 30:17). The absence of that healing is now announced as permanent. Peter Craigie (Jeremiah 1-25, Word Biblical Commentary, 1991) notes that the shift from reshapable clay to shattered ceramic maps precisely onto the shift from the conditional warnings of earlier chapters to the unconditional judgment oracles that dominate from chapter 19 onward. The clay of God's patience has been fired by Judah's prolonged apostasy into an irreversible sentence."
